{"id":"1902.10673","submitter":"Ryan Babbush","authors":"Ian D. Kivlichan, Craig Gidney, Dominic W. Berry, Nathan Wiebe, Jarrod\n  McClean, Wei Sun, Zhang Jiang, Nicholas Rubin, Austin Fowler, Al\\'an\n  Aspuru-Guzik, Hartmut Neven and Ryan Babbush","title":"Improved Fault-Tolerant Quantum Simulation of Condensed-Phase Correlated\n  Electrons via Trotterization","comments":"45 pages, 15 figures. Only difference from v3 is change to CC BY 4.0\n  license","journal-ref":"Quantum 4, 296 (2020)","doi":"10.22331/q-2020-07-16-296","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph physics.chem-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Recent work has deployed linear combinations of unitaries techniques to\nreduce the cost of fault-tolerant quantum simulations of correlated electron\nmodels. Here, we show that one can sometimes improve upon those results with\noptimized implementations of Trotter-Suzuki-based product formulas. We show\nthat low-order Trotter methods perform surprisingly well when used with phase\nestimation to compute relative precision quantities (e.g. energies per unit\ncell), as is often the goal for condensed-phase systems. In this context,\nsimulations of the Hubbard and plane-wave electronic structure models with $N <\n10^5$ fermionic modes can be performed with roughly $O(1)$ and $O(N^2)$ T\ncomplexities. We perform numerics revealing tradeoffs between the error and\ngate complexity of a Trotter step; e.g., we show that split-operator techniques\nhave less Trotter error than popular alternatives. By compiling to surface code\nfault-tolerant gates and assuming error rates of one part per thousand, we show\nthat one can error-correct quantum simulations of interesting, classically\nintractable instances with a few hundred thousand physical qubits.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 27 Feb 2019 18:17:53 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 16 Aug 2019 21:18:27 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 10 Jul 2020 01:40:49 G